; it also causes constant flurries of commentary and controversy. Concerns about ‘borders’ and ‘boundaries’, a questioning of documentary’s claim to represent the real, doubts about the popular audience’s ability to cope with new approaches to the ideas of witness, testimony and confession, authenticity and truth - all fuel the debate.This new edition situates docudrama and its ongoing debates within a newly vibrant and still highly contentious field of practice. This book will interest readers - academic and general - with an interest in fact-based drama in film, theatre and television  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistorical dramaxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision playsxHistory and criticism. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Documentary.2bisacsh  a1990s co-pros.  aAmerican television.  aBritish television.  aGriersonian documentary.  aTodd Gitlin.  afiction.  afilm.  ahybridization.  akeywords.  amass audience.  amedia-literate environment.  amodern docudrama.  apersonal stories.  apre-production research.  atelevision production.  aterrorism.1 aPaget, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779814540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847798145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847798145/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles